The pyramid is very pretty: it contains gold sparkle ( gold leaf?) upon which sits a copper coil, and what appears to be a ~20 mm amethyst “globe”. Mine did not come with the wooden platform and lights, unfortunately. When I tried to find the contact info for the company, I couldn't seem to locate it. The box states “Made in China”. If I received this as a holiday gift from an acquaintance, especially if the lighted base were to be included, I think I would be pleased. I actually do feel better energy since I've been wearing the pendant and displaying the pyramid.

title: Pretty, Fun, Good Energy
text: While scanning over various suggested items on Amazon, I paused when I saw this item. The name, orgonite, reminds me of something I read a long time ago, about a certain Wilhelm Reich. Reich was an immigrant scientist who theorized that what he called “orgone energy”, ie, the life force energy emitted during sexual orgasm, had the power to heal. He even invented an “orgone machine” and evidently had a following until he was shut down by what some say were the feds. So, of course with a story like that, I knew I had to get this to check it out! My orgonite/resin/amethyst/copper coil/ gold leaf flaked pendant and pyramid arrived in a sturdy, pretty, giftable  cardboard box, within which resided a velvet draw string bag containing these handmade amulets. Unfortunately, I did not receive either the wooden base and/ or lights to use as a stand. When I tried to contact the company to ask about it, I quickly discovered that there was no contact information to be found. That being said, I enjoy wearing my new pendant, which has a sparkly back, and a pic of what I'm assuming is the tree of life on the front. It came attached to a bolo style cord to wear around the neck. I'm also enjoying the pretty resin pyramid, especially now that I've rigged it up with my own fiber optic light box that I use with my other crystals. Other than not finding any contact info for the company, I can't say I see anything negative at all. It was a fun, pretty gift that I greatly enjoyed receiving.

title: Excellent
text:
Liquid Castile soap brings back old memory of scents and stages of 'handcrafted' and none of that distinctive sting. It's terrific. It's thinner and different from the big factory brands. As boiling whole hogs start the process, maybe it's vegetarian now.

It brings back old memories and cleans your hands.

Soap-making tradition on the large family farm was an institution ... mom, g-g-ma, g-ma, g-g aunts & uncles, aunts and uncles, dozens of cousins. It was a late-fall, early winter tradition, as I recall, shortly after the outdoor open fire, copper vat (we kids figured you could boil one of us in them), sales quantity, apple butter endlessly stirred by the cousins.

So I'm maybe ten years old and beginning my hired-hand, unpaid farm apprentice-ship. My recollection of homemade soap's main ingredients includes strange, clear slabs of jelly-like rendered hog fat, sacks of lye (bad stuff), and charcoal, among other things likely 200, maybe 300 years old. From these bases came a line of products. Pine tar soap for work hands, lye soap bars for dishes and laundry, and various soaps and cleansers made from dilution of the lye soap. The only soaps purchased included Ivory, Murphy's oil soap, and PineSol.

Yes, the lye soap could sting. We kids just thought the sting was what clean felt like.

My proper gem ID equipment is too deeply packed away to conclusively ID as aquamarine. But, from experience and hardness check, it's in the aquamarine class hardness. There are named variations based on crystal structures, some rarer than aquamarine, that formed in the same ancient hot spring vent matrix where this formed that might be confusable with the aquamarine. Yes, there are aquamarine-colored emeralds, but this isn't that. The matrix cooled too quickly (geologically) to grow into a larger clear form.

text:
I've had this (the 8 x 18 version) for two years and it's still works as well as the day I got it. The cover is removable for washing. This has quite literally been a life saver during COVID. I cannot go to PT during the pandemic and this heating pack is the only thing that makes it possible for me to sleep. Much safer than an electric heating pad. I can heat it to just the right temperature for me and place it under my back and it will relax the muscles so I can get to sleep. It naturally absorbs just enough moisture from the air so that when you heat it, it's not a dry heat. And the body heat from lying on it will absorb into it through the night keeping it warm & enabling it to maintain some of the heating properties.

Be very careful about how much you heat it, especially if you are going to be leaning or lying on it. It will feel hotter on your back (or anywhere else) than on your hands.

text: I have had this for about a month now and I can say that it is a high quality product. The cane has a nice heft- very solid. The head is carved from two solid pieces of hardwood laminated together to create a symmetrical wood grain (you can easily see this in the pattern on the back of the skull in my photos). When it comes to individually hand-made items, there is always a fear that what you get may differ significantly from the listing's images. In this case, however, the skull is carved just as shown in the item description. One of the things that made me decide on this cane was the simple, realistic skull; it's not overly stylized as I often see on products like this; i.e., it is not made to look "evil" or "angry" or have fangs or anything silly like that. It's just a pure, fairly realistic representation of a skull, which makes it classy enough for formal use, but stylish and well-made even for everyday use. The head can be screwed off and replaced if desired. Mine came with a spare rubber end cap, black rubber, small enough to keep the elegant, classy look, but large enough to feel sturdy and grip well. The cane feels very good in my hand; the curve of the skull is easy to grip. I bought this for everyday use due to a disability, and whatever the situation it gets loads of compliments. I am 100% happy that I made this purchase.

I am a woman and, out of all IA sample scents I tried before, Saint Julep was the only one I loved. I ordered the 1.7 oz spray for my birthday. For me, it was a wonderful summer fragrance choice — the scent is evocative of wood, fresh sweaty skin, summer heat, hay, tangerine rind and, of course, mint. I loved the description of it. Saint Julep is not sweet and not your typical aftershave-like “unisex” option, either. I think it is truly a scent that could be used by anyone who is not into florals/gourmands. IA creator(s) tend to add something “burnt” to their compositions (“Mom, I smell like a pirate!”, said my daughter when she tried one of the samples), which I don't like necessarily, but here the accent is softer and doesn't bother me. It is more peppery than smoky. So, overall, it is a very special scent that transports you straight into a hot summer day when you close your eyes. The mint is at the heart of this composition and gives it a uniquely relaxed Southern character.
That said, the sillage is almost non-existent, and it is a huge flaw. For this price, it is rather disappointing. I would give this fragrance 5 stars if it had more staying power, but there is barely any.
Overall: thoroughly enjoy the scent when I put it on, literally. I don't really smell anything in 20 minutes.
